2.2. Fates of Marine MPs
Generally, debris in any water body will ultimately enter the ocean. Transported by water power and wind power, microplastics gradually migrate and diffuse through the ocean, eventually becoming as ubiquitous as they are today, ranging from the large ocean gyres (e.g., the Pacific Ocean [
]; the Atlantic Ocean [
]; Indian Ocean [
]) to the polar regions and equator, from densely populated areas to remote islands, and from beaches down to the abysses of the sea [
]. They come in various shapes, with fibers being the most common form, followed by fragments.

