Bioavailability strongly relies on the physiochemical properties of microplastics, like their size, shape, and density [
]. The conclusion is that the size of microplastics is the most important factor. As the size decreases, the potential of bioaccumulation and bioavailability increase [
], because microplastics with smaller size are similar to planktonic organisms, and could be easily mistakenly ingested by zooplankton [
]. The irregular shape of plastic particles or fibers results in different bioavailability [
